    strengths: "Chiang Mai University's prestigious teaching hospital with over 200 physicians and specialists. Offers the same high-calibre surgeons as premium private hospitals at roughly one-third the price — a cardiac surgery quoted at 1.5 million THB elsewhere costs around 450,000 THB here. Exceptional breadth of specialties including dedicated Cardiac, Stroke, GI/Liver, and Oncology centers. Highly rated by both locals and expats (4.9 stars, 12,700+ Google reviews). Minimal wait times despite no appointment. Foreign Center available for international patients. 24-hour ICU, CCU, hemodialysis, and ambulance. Academic excellence from CMU Faculty of Medicine affiliation.",
    weaknesses: "As a semi-government university hospital, the environment is more utilitarian than private hospital luxury. English proficiency varies significantly by department — not all staff are fluent. International billing and insurance coordination is less streamlined than at JCI-accredited private hospitals. Can be busy/crowded with outpatient volume. No JCI accreditation. Limited luxury amenities compared to Bangkok Hospital or Chiang Mai Ram.",
    summary: "Sriphat Medical Center is the academic hospital of Chiang Mai University's Faculty of Medicine and the outstanding value option in northern Thailand. It combines genuine tertiary-care depth — cardiac surgery, oncology, nephrology, neurology — with public-university pricing that is dramatically lower than private competitors. The same specialists often work both here and at private hospitals. With 4.9-star Google ratings and over 12,700 reviews, it enjoys extraordinary patient trust. Its Foreign Center provides some international support, but insurance direct-billing and English fluency are inconsistent. Ideal for cost-conscious expats and medical tourists willing to trade five-star amenities for world-class medicine at Thai government prices.",
